results.name: a(n) is the number of ways the set {1^3, 2^3, ..., n^3} can be partitioned into two sets of equal sums.
link: Alois P. Heinz and Ray Chandler, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..130 (first 100 terms from Alois P. Heinz)
formula: a(n) is half the coefficient of x^0 in product(x^(k^3)+x^(k^-3), k=1..n).
maple: A113263:=proc(n) local i,p,t; t:= NULL; p:=1; for i to n do p:=p*(x^(i^3)+x^(-i^3)); t:=t,coeff(p,x,0)/2; od; t; end;
mathematica: p = 1; t = {}; Do[p = Expand[p(x^(n^3) + x^(-n^3))]; AppendTo[t, Select[ p, NumberQ[ # ] &]/2], {n, 56}]; t (* _Robert G. Wilson v_ *)
